#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:9 app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:101
msgid "Foreword"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:13
msgid ""
"This book contains all the competitive scenarios for Space Empires 4X, "
"Close Encounters, Replicators, and All Good Things. The base game and "
"both previous expansions are necessary to take advantage of all the "
"options found here. These rules assume that you are using the updated "
"player aid cards provided with All Good Things. Cross-references to "
"sections will be included in parentheses, e.g., (5.7). References to the "
"Master Rule Book and the Solo/Co-Op Scenario Book will be notated "
"accordingly, e.g. (MRB 5.5) or (SSB 8.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:17
msgid "Standard Rules for Competitive Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:21
msgid ""
"1.1.1 Player At-Start Forces: Unless otherwise specified, in each "
"scenario each player gets the following:\n"
"• A fully developed 30 CP Homeworld. When playing with the optional rules"
" for Facilities (MRB 36.0), the 20 CP Homeworld counter is used instead."
"\n"
"• Three Colony Ships, one Miner, four Shipyards (SY), and three Scouts "
"(SC) at their Homeworld.\n"
"• One Flagship (optional, MRB 23.0).\n"
"\n"
"1.1.2 Customizable: Give each rule a shot before you judge it. A lot of "
"thought and play went into them. However, once familiar with the game, "
"feel free to play the game any way you want -- this game is meant to be "
"customized. You won't offend the designer!\n"
"\n"
"1.1.3 Galaxy Setup: Unless otherwise specified, Home System markers of a "
"player's color are placed in hexes that represent their home territory "
"and Deep Space System markers (white) are placed in all other hexes -- "
"even hexes that could possibly have been a Home System area if there were"
" more players. Excess System markers are set aside.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.4 Warp Points and Doomsday Machines: Warp Point and Doomsday Machine "
"counters should not be removed from the game at setup. However, unless "
"you are playing with the appropriate optional rule (MRB 28.2; MRB 29.0), "
"they are considered \"open space\" and are removed from the game when "
"flipped. Feel free to do this with every counter players agree not to use"
" in their game.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.5 2-Player Victory Condition: The victory condition for each "
"scenario, unless stated otherwise, is to destroy your opponent's "
"Homeworld. However, the winning side can often become obvious before "
"that, and it is suggested that you end the game at that point.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.6 Multiplayer Victory Condition: Victory in multiplayer games, unless"
" stated otherwise, is to destroy one opponent's Homeworld. When any "
"player destroys any other player's Homeworld, they become the victor.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.7 Multiplayer Short Game Victory Condition (Colony Points): In "
"addition to the condition in 1.1.6 above:\n"
"• A player wins by scoring 3 Colony Points. A player gets a Colony Point "
"by:\n"
"  - Destroying (not damaging) another player's Colony. This includes new "
"Colonies, but not Colony Ships. Once gained, this Colony Point cannot be "
"lost. Capturing another player's Colony using ground combat also counts "
"(MRB 21.0).\n"
"  - By having a 5 CP Colony in Deep Space or an opponent's Home System. "
"This Colony Point is not permanent.\n"
"  - A captured Colony may count for up to two Colony Points.\n"
"• A player wins the instant they score their third Colony Point and the "
"game ends immediately, even if it is mid-turn.\n"
"• If multiple players score their third Colony Point in the same Economic"
" Phase, the win goes to the player with the most Colony Points. "
"Tiebreaker: CP value of all combat-capable ships on the board.\n"
"• If playing with Variable Map setup (3.2, 4.2), Colony Points are only "
"scored for destroying Colonies -- not for having them.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.8 Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition: Players are eliminated "
"when their Homeworld is destroyed. Remove all of their pieces and "
"Colonies. The winner is the last player standing. A player that "
"eliminates another player gets a bonus 30 CPs in the next Economic Phase."
" If the conquered player had technology the victor does not possess, they"
" may choose one level of two separate technologies and mark them as "
"researched. Homeworlds re-colonized by other players act as normal "
"Colonies (at most 5 CPs).\n"
"\n"
"1.1.9 \"Sinister\" Victory Condition: A player wins by eliminating the "
"Homeworld of the player on their left. This creates two fronts per player"
" (one offensive, one defensive) and reduces the likelihood of two players"
" ganging up on a third.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.10 Simultaneous Play: To speed up play, many parts of Space Empires "
"were designed to be done simultaneously. When playing with experienced "
"players, it is suggested that all players conduct their turns at once and"
" only wait for people in order to keep everyone in the same Economic "
"Phase. Switch to sequential turns when only two rows of deep space remain"
" unexplored between players.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.11 Quick Start Variant: After setting up, flip all Home System "
"markers and place a full-strength Colony on all non-barren planets. "
"Players do not start with any Colony Ships.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.12 (Small) Handicap Rule: Use this rule to provide a small advantage "
"to a less-experienced player by increasing their CP income during the "
"early game. During each Economic Phase, the income of that player's "
"Colonies will increase by two steps. 10 CP Planets grow to 5 CP then to "
"10 CP the following phase.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.13 Variable but Balanced Home Systems: In this variant, all players "
"have the same markers in their Home Systems, but no player is aware of "
"which markers are in play.\n"
"• All players set aside from their Home Systems: two non-barren Planets, "
"two 5-Mineral counters, one Asteroid, and one Nebula.\n"
"• Each player also sets aside all 8 of the new Home System markers "
"(marked with a \"v\" on the front side): one Supernova, one Fold in "
"Space, two 10-Mineral counters, one Space Wreck, one Space Pirate, and "
"two 10 CP Planets.\n"
"• All these counters are organized into stacks of one counter of each "
"type per player. This creates 14 stacks.\n"
"• Players collectively choose 6 of the 14 stacks randomly and blindly. "
"Each player takes their 6 markers and shuffles them into their Home "
"System markers before setup."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:61
msgid ""
"1.1.9 “Sinister” Victory Condition: A player wins by eliminating the "
"Homeworld of the player on their left. This creates two fronts for each "
"player (one offensive and one defensive) and reduces the likelihood of "
"two players ganging up to eliminate a third. The archaic definition of "
"sinister is “related to the left side/left-handed.” The notion that left-"
" handedness was a sign of sin/evil has led to the modern usage of "
"sinister to mean so."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:62
msgid ""
"1.1.12 (Small) Handicap Rule: Use this rule to provide a small advantage "
"to a less-experienced player by increasing their CP income during the "
"early game. During each Economic Phase, the income of that player’s "
"Colonies will increase by two steps. For example, a Colony Ship is "
"flipped to its Colony side and a “3 Colony” marker is placed on top "
"instead of a “1 Colony.” 1.1.13 Variable but Balanced Home Systems: In "
"this variant, all players have the same markers in their Home Systems, "
"but no player is aware of which markers are in play. • All players set "
"aside the following markers from their Home Systems: two non-barren "
"Planets, two 5-Mineral counters, one Asteroid, and one Nebula. • Each "
"player then also sets aside all 8 of the new Home System markers (these "
"are marked with a “v” on the front side): one Supernova, one Fold in "
"Space, two 10-Mineral counters, one Space Wreck, one Space Pirate, and "
"two 10 CP Planets (see below). • All these counters are organized into "
"stacks of one counter of each type per player. This will create 14 "
"stacks. EXAMPLE: In a 3-player game, there will be 14 stacks of 3 "
"counters each – one from each player: One stack with one Asteroids from "
"each player; two stacks with one 10-Mineral counter from each player, "
"etc. • Players collectively choose 6 of the 14 stacks. These stacks "
"should be chosen randomly and blindly so all players are unaware of which"
" markers will be included in the game. Each player takes their 6 markers "
"and shuffles them back into their Home System markers before setting up "
"their Home System."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:63
msgid ""
"10 CP Planets will grow to 5 CP like any other Colony and will then grow "
"to 10 CP the following phase. At 5 CP, place a flipped Colony Ship on "
"top; remove it when the Colony reaches 10 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:68 app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:150
msgid "Gameplay Advice"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:72
msgid ""
"The play time for this game is in the 1 to 4-hour range for a 2-player "
"game, depending on the scenario. For multiplayer games, the play time "
"will be at the higher end of that range.\n"
"• Start with just the basic rules. While they are fairly simple, the game"
" offers a lot of choices and decisions.\n"
"• Start with the Small 2-Player Scenario. Experienced players can finish "
"in less than an hour and a half.\n"
"• For the first multiplayer game, play teams. It will drastically shorten"
" the playing time.\n"
"• Be aggressive! This is a game that rewards aggressive play."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:80
msgid "Player Alliances"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:84
msgid ""
"Some 3-Player or 4-Player scenarios include rules called UNEASY ALLIANCE "
"or BLOOD BROTHERS. When using either of these rules in any scenario, "
"teammates win or lose the game together. Also, you may not capture "
"Colonies from your allies with Ground Units (MRB 21.0) nor may you use "
"Boarding Ships (MRB 19.0) on your allies. You may never bombard Colonies "
"that your allies originally colonized.\n"
"\n"
"1.3.1 UNEASY ALLIANCE: Teammates may never stack units of any kind in the"
" same hex and may not use each other's MS Pipelines.\n"
"\n"
"1.3.2 BLOOD BROTHERS: Teammates execute their turns at the same time, may"
" stack together, may attack together, and may use each other's MS "
"Pipelines for movement. However, they may not share research or CPs."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:92
msgid "Definitions for All Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:96
msgid ""
"• Homeworld setup: Unless otherwise noted in the scenario rules, "
"Homeworlds may be placed in a player's Home System hex marked with a red "
"\"H\" or a red-dashed line.\n"
"• Hexes outside of the playing area are NOT playable."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:105
msgid ""
"This book contains all the solitaire and cooperative scenarios for Space "
"Empires 4X, Close Encounters, Replicators, and All Good Things. Both "
"previous expansions are necessary to take advantage of all the options "
"found here. These rules assume that you are using the updated player "
"sheets provided with All Good Things. Cross-references to sections will "
"be included in parentheses, e.g., (5.7). References to the Master Rule "
"Book and the Competitive Scenario Book will be notated accordingly, e.g. "
"(MRB 5.5) or (CSB 8.0).\n"
"\n"
"Sections 1-12 are a reprinting of previously published Solo and Coop "
"scenarios with minor updates and errata included. These updates are the "
"result of over a decade of feedback and great alternative scenario ideas "
"from players online, see Solo Team Credits (p.51). Two additional "
"scenarios for use with these previously published game modes are also "
"included.\n"
"\n"
"Additionally, we have added a new mode of Solo/Coop play called the AP "
"Bot. This new mode lets players play virtually any scenario Solitaire or "
"Cooperatively by using some new mechanics to emulate a real player and "
"preserve the element of surprise often missing or lessened in the "
"previously published Solo/Coop scenarios. These rules do not replace "
"those scenarios, but do give players the opportunity to play almost any "
"scenario, that normally required a human opponent, solitaire or "
"cooperatively."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:113
msgid "Standard Rules for Solo/Coop Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/scenario_rulebooks.py:117
msgid ""
"1.1.1 Player At-Start Forces: Unless otherwise specified, in each "
"scenario each player gets the following:\n"
"• A fully developed 30 CP Homeworld. When playing with the optional rules"
" for Facilities (MRB 36.0), the 20 CP Homeworld counter is used instead."
"\n"
"• Three Colony Ships, one Miner, four Shipyards (SY), and three Scouts "
"(SC) at their Homeworld.\n"
"• One Flagship (optional, MRB 23.0).\n"
"\n"
"Play Note: The Technology Head Start Scenario Card (see the Card "
"Manifest) is not available for solitaire or cooperative scenarios.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.2 Customizable: Give each rule a shot before you judge it. A lot of "
"thought and play went into them. However, this game is meant to be "
"customized. You won't offend the designer!\n"
"\n"
"1.1.3 Galaxy Setup: Each scenario will indicate the starting location for"
" Home System markers, Deep Space markers and other relevant locations.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.4 Warp Points: Warp Point counters should not be removed from the "
"game at setup. However, unless you are playing with the appropriate "
"optional rule (MRB 28.2), they are considered \"open space\" and are "
"removed from the game when flipped.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.5 Doomsday Machines and Space Amoebas: Deep Space Doomsday Machines "
"and Space Amoebas should not be used in the Deep Space portion of the map"
" in the coop scenarios.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.6 Galactic Capitol: If used, players may not bombard, capture, or "
"deliver Minerals to the Galactic Capitol (MRB 28.1). Players may place "
"Ground Units on the Galactic Capitol to help defend against Alien Player "
"invasion and bombardment or DM attacks (MRB 29.0). Advanced Bases and "
"Starbases (MRB 38.5) may NOT be built in the Galactic Capitol hex.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.7 Alternate Empires: Players may choose to use Alternate Empires (MRB"
" 24.0) in any solo or cooperative scenario. However, Alternate Empires "
"cannot be used to represent an Alien Player in any of the non-AP Bot "
"scenarios.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.8 Empire Advantages: Empire Advantages (MRB 10.0) can be used by "
"human players with any solo or cooperative scenario. Note that doing so "
"will reduce the game's difficulty.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.9 Lost in Space Markers: If units move onto a Lost in Space marker, "
"designate one of the six surrounding hexes as \"1\" and count around them"
" clockwise to \"6.\" Roll a die, rerolling 7-10. The units are sent to "
"the resulting hex.\n"
"\n"
"1.1.10 Optional First Player Bidding in Doomsday Machine Scenarios: The "
"DM starts the game as first player and will bid when appropriate. The DM "
"bid is resolved after human players have completed their Econ Phases. The"
" DM only bids if a DM is on the board. If a Human player wins the bid, "
"they may determine player order as normal. While the DM is first player "
"the Human Players may decide and commit to their own play order during "
"each Econ Phase.\n"
"Bid Amount: The DM bids the lower of 2d10 but gets these CP for free. If "
"both die result in the same number, add this number to the result of "
"another lower of 2d10 (these die rolls \"explode\"). If doubles again, "
"repeat this again but this is the final result."
msgstr ""

